## Key Takeaways

Here’s my take on why the Reddit strategy works so well:

The AI trusts it more than brands. AI systems are trained to prioritize human-to-human advice. Since Reddit is built on unfiltered discussion, it’s seen as more credible than a polished, sales-heavy company blog.

It’s a shortcut to authority. You don’t have to spend years building up your own site's reputation. If you post a genuinely helpful answer in the right community, you’re basically "piggybacking" on Reddit’s massive trust score with search engines.

The AI loves the format. AI models need more than just one-sided marketing fluff; they look for pros, cons, and real-world experiences. Reddit threads naturally provide that balanced, "conversation" style that makes it easy for an AI to pull a complete answer.

Don't try to "market" there. The second you sound like an ad, the community (and the AI) will tune you out. The only way this actually works is if you’re genuinely solving a problem for real people.

Target the right spots. It’s not about how many posts you make; it’s about being in the specific subreddits where my actual target audience is asking questions. If the community upvotes my answer, it's basically a green light for the AI to cite me as a top source.

